Gapminder

For this assignment, we are going to use the dataset gapminder. Gapminder includes information about economics, population, and life expectancy from countries all over the world. You will need to install it before use.

  1. How many countries are represented in this dataset? Make a table and a plot that shows the number of countries by continent.
gapminder %>% 
  group_by(continent) %>% 
  summarize(total_countries = n_distinct(country))
## # A tibble: 5 × 2
##   continent total_countries
##   <fct>               <int>
## 1 Africa                 52
## 2 Americas               25
## 3 Asia                   33
## 4 Europe                 30
## 5 Oceania                 2
gapminder %>% 
  group_by(continent) %>% 
  summarize(total_countries = n_distinct(country)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = continent, y = total_countries, fill = continent))+
  geom_col()+
  labs(title = "Countries by Continent",
       x = "Continents",
       y = "Number of Countries")+
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = rel(1.5), hjust = 0.5))

  1. Which country has the largest population growth since 1952? Show this as a table.
gapminder %>% 
  select(pop, country, year) %>% 
  mutate(year = as.factor(year)) %>% 
  filter(year == "1952" | year == "2007") %>% 
  pivot_wider(values_from = pop,
              names_from = year) %>% 
  rename(pop_1952 = "1952", pop_2007 = "2007") %>% 
  mutate(pop_growth = pop_2007 - pop_1952) %>% 
  arrange(-pop_growth)

China had the largest population growth since 1952.

  1. Make a plot that shows population growth for the country you found in question #3. This plot should show the change over time.
gapminder %>% 
  filter(country == "China") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = year, y = pop, color = country))+
  geom_line()+
  geom_point()+
  labs(title = "Population Growth in China", x = "Year", y = "Population")+
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = rel(1.5), hjust = 0.5))

On average, global life expectancy has increased between 1952 and 2007.

  1. Make a plot that shows how mean life expectancy has changed over time for each continent. What is your interpretation of what happened in Africa between 1987 and 2002?
gapminder %>% 
  group_by(continent, year) %>% 
  summarise(min_life_exp = min(lifeExp), max_life_exp = max(lifeExp), avg_life_exp = mean(lifeExp), .groups = 'keep') %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = year, y = avg_life_exp, color = continent))+
  geom_line()+
  geom_point()+
  labs(title = "Average Life Expectancy Over Time per Continent",
       x = "Year",
       y = "Average Life Expectancy (yrs)")+
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = rel(1.5), hjust = 0.5))

I would think something like a war or disease caused many people to lose their lives which would cause the life expectancy to be stagnant for a couple of years in Africa.

  1. We are interested in the relationship between per capita GDP and life expectancy; i.e. does having more money help you live longer? Show this as a plot.
gapminder %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = gdpPercap, y = lifeExp, color = continent))+
  geom_point()+
  geom_jitter()+
  labs(title = "Per Capita GDP and Life Expectancy",
       x = "Per Capita GDP",
       y = "Life Expectancy")+
  scale_x_log10()+
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = rel(1.5), hjust = 0.5))

There seems to be slight trend of higher per capita GDP being associated with higher life expectancy.

  1. Which five countries have had the highest GDP per capita growth over the years represented in this dataset? Show this as a table.
gapminder %>% 
  select(gdpPercap, country, year) %>% 
  mutate(year = as.factor(year)) %>% 
  filter(year == "1952" | year == "2007") %>% 
  pivot_wider(values_from = gdpPercap,
              names_from = year) %>% 
  rename(gdp_1952 = "1952", gdp_2007 = "2007") %>% 
  mutate(gdp_growth = gdp_2007 - gdp_1952) %>% 
  arrange(-gdp_growth) %>% 
  top_n(5, gdp_growth)

  1. Do one analysis of your choice that includes a table and plot as outputs.
    Which European country has had the highest life expectancy increase from 1952 to 2007 and how did it change over time?
gapminder %>% 
  select(country, year, continent, lifeExp) %>% 
  mutate(year = as.factor(year)) %>% 
  filter(continent == "Europe") %>% 
  filter(year == 1952 | year == 2007) %>%
  group_by(year) %>% 
  pivot_wider(names_from = year,
              values_from = lifeExp) %>% 
  rename(life_exp_1952 = "1952", life_exp_2007 = "2007") %>% 
  mutate(life_exp_growth = life_exp_2007 - life_exp_1952) %>% 
  arrange(-life_exp_growth)
